61":"1261","1150":"1150","about 1208":"circa 1208","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","1279":"1279","1223":"1223","circa 1261":"circa 1261","1255":"1255","1200":"1200","about 1258":"circa 1258","1208":"1208","Compton, Devonshire, England":"Compton, Devon, England","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Schotland","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Compton Wynyates, Warwickshire, England":"Compton Wynyates, Warwickshire, England"},"en":{"about 1208–circa 1261":"about 1208–about 1261","1208–1261":"1208–1261","1200–1279":"1200–1279","1258–1279":"1258–1279","1150–1223":"1150–1223","1261":"1261","1150":"1150","about 1208":"about 1208","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1224":"1224","1279":"1279","1223":"1223","circa 1261":"about 1261","1255":"1255","1200":"1200","about 1258":"about 1258","1208":"1208","Compton, Devonshire, England":"Compton, Devon, England","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Compton Wynyates, Warwickshire, England":"Compton Wynyates, Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Strathearn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Strathearn in Perthshire. The placename means ‘the valley of the river Earn’, from Gaelic <i>srath</i> ‘valley’ + the river name Earn."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":7,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":16,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":51,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Strathearn was born about 1208, in